4.75/5  rDev +2.8%look: 4.75 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75Canned 8/17/16. Consumed 9/1/16.
A: Pours an incredibly murky gold that looks almost grey in the glass due to lack of transparency. This beer is as turbid as they come, without an ounce of transparency. It's almost gravy-like in its haze. About a finger of white head on the pour fades in a minute to a ring of tiny white bubbles. Major alcohol legs are apparent on the glass.
S: BIG tart grapefruit on the nose with sweeter supporting notes played by other citrus and tropical fruits (orange, pineapple, tangerine). Very pithy grapefruit. Also getting a bunch of resinous, grassy dankness following the fruit notes.
T: Intense tropical fruit juice up front. Guava, pineapple, and spicy mango. Tons of orange (juice and pith). Little bit of bready malt mid-palette, but then a BIG burst of resinous, herbaceous grass on the finish. Finish is really spicy and powerful; notes of freshly ground spices sting the roof of the mouth that could easily be mistaken for booziness or bitterness (though there's a bunch of the latter too). UPDATE: upon consumption of second can (9/10, 3+ weeks after canning), I got a lot more sweet, exotic fruit on the taste than the spicy, pithy grapefruit assault I got the first time. Second time around, the taste is a beautiful medley of tropical and citrus fruits. Upping this from 4.75 to 5.
M: Big creamy mouthfeel. Smooth and well carbonated, despite the appearance. Little bit of heat from the alcohol on the back of the throat, but nothing unpleasant. Medium plus bitterness on the finish is accentuated by the aforementioned spicy grass flavor that lingers on the roof of the mouth. Medium plus dryness makes this dangerously drinkable.
O: This is a big DIPA. I totally understand why Trillium pretty much exclusively describes this beer by the amount of hops they use in its creation. For all intents and purposes, Headroom is an absolute hop explosion. It unapologetically showcases every aspect of its hop profile--the pungent aromas, intense flavors, and resinous bitterness--without restraint. To the most passionate hopheads, Headroom is a must-try. But for me, it's a bit too harsh (maybe it needs some more time?). After drinking a Very Hazy from Tree House last night, there is no comparison. But while I prefer the soft, delicate fruitiness of VH to the harsh, spicy grassiness of Headroom, others may not. I think this may be a perfect beer for some, so in that sense, the hype very well may be justified.
Also, as a side note, this actually reminded me quite a bit of Crucial Taunt from the Veil, which, while slightly more malt-forward, presented the a similar profile of tropical, citric, and dank aromas/flavors. 2,671 charactersavas, Sep 02, 2016
4.92/5  rDev +6.5%look: 5 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 5L: Insanely hazy (bordering on murky) deep burnt orange, honeycomb, and apricot hues with a loose white head that recedes quickly
S: Grapefruit, starfruit, tangerines, and a bit of dankness
T: Huge burst of citrus and tropical fruits is swiftly met by an audacious cascade of hops, pine, and grapefruit pith bitterness - truly a roller-coaster of flavors in every sip
F: Typical Trillium body with soft carbonation
O: Wow - this bold DIPA truly lives up to its reputation and they weren't kidding about how hop-forward it is. Rest assured though, the hoppy and piney flavors are well balanced by Trillium's trademark juiciness. For those West Coasters hesitant to jump into the NE-style IPAs, this beer could serve as a wonderful gateway IPA for you. Overall, Headroom is an aggressive, flavorful beer that demands your attention and makes a unique mark in Trillium's library of world-class beers - not something easily done. Truly one to savor. 945 charactersFireman_RK, Sep 02, 2016
