4.2/5  rDev -9.1%look: 3.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 3.75 |  overall: 4.25Drank from a 1 pint can purchased at Trillium Brewing Company, Boston, MA
08/17/16
Served in a snifter
Huge thanks to my amazing wife Becky for waiting two-and-a-half hours in line at the release.
Ridiculously turbid appearance. I have seen many a murky New England-style hoppy beer, but this truly brought things to another level. The grapefruit juice-like body was capped by a fleeting film of tiny white bubbles that dissolved within seconds.
The nose was pure hoppy bliss. Uber fruity and bright. Citrus notes dominated. Loads of juicy orange and tangerine. Good dose of zesty white grapefruit. Tropical fruits also came through strong. Mango was most apparent. Some musty passionfruit was also noticeable. Bit of dank weediness as well.
Zesty citrus notes came through big time in the flavor profile. Lots of white grapefruit. Hefty dose of tangy tangerine. Some orange and orange pith too. Lemony in the center. Almost a bit sour. The beer finished with huge notes of pithy white grapefruit rind. Very dry and bitter. Oily, resinous hop notes lingered after the swallow.
The mouthfeel was lighter than I was anticipating and contained a fizzy, moderate effervescence that frothed up nicely on the palate. Smooth and fluffy. A touch airy however.
I am typically a huge fan of Trillium's hoppy beers but was a bit disappointed with this one. Although fantastic in aroma, Headroom had a somewhat unappealing appearance, a thinner mouthfeel, and was much more pithy and bitter than any of their other hoppy beers. I am surprised to see that this is one of their top-rated offerings. 1,589 charactersDamian, Aug 29, 2016
