4.47/5  rDev -3.2%look: 4.75 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 5 |  overall: 4.5Purchased August 21, consumed August 22. One of the lucky few to land and consume out of a growler.
A: Hazy, muted gold. MURKY. Moreso than your typical Trillium, which is saying a lot. So cloudy it looks like a glass full of golden beach sand. You can judge this book by its cover, it's going to be good, and it's going to be HOPPY.
S: Kitchen immediately smelled of beer when I opened the growler. Floral, bright, fruity. Not as pronounced sticky sweetness as some of their double dry hopped offerings, but it's potent. Grassier and drier smell than fort point, congress st, etc. 
T: Very bright, dank, heady, fruity. Starts of grassy, fruit kicks in in the aftertaste. Not as smooth as usual, but I don't mind. This beer was made to showcase hops, and hops are what you get. Tastes like I'm inside a 95 degree room with 100% humidity where it's just me and a bounty of hops. Sticky, piney; the bitterness almost overwhelms but walks the line just right. This is one to be sipped.
O: This is really really awesome. Worth the wait in line to try something a bit off the Trillium beaten path. Just an absolute hop assault, without a malty backbone supporting it. To me, this is a wonderful thing. Often times I find malt/sugar(ie dfh 90 minute) gets in the way of what a hophead like me wants. To those who missed out,  I think this beer would be comparable to  King Julius but without their signature softness.
I've purchased 4 bottles as well, I'm going to try and save a few and see how these taste after a few weeks. What did Boston do before Trillium existed? With offerings like this, my trips to Vermont solely for Heady Topper are no longer as frequent. I enjoy their beers almost as much as Hill Farmstead.
EDIT; 08-27-16 - a new batch of headroom. hopefully this is an annual thing because damn is it good. just as hazy as ever. juicy and dank with that signature trillium bite. Worth the wait...and the worth the god damn price too. 1,950 charactersJonnyJuicebox, Aug 22, 2015
